[1] Crow and mosquito pools - Illinois
Date: Thu 13 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News-Medial, Thu 13 May 2004 [edited]


Illinois: 1st West Nile virus positive results: crow and mosquito pools
-----------------------------------------------
A dead crow and 2 pools of mosquitoes collected in DuPage County have been
reported West Nile virus-positive; the 1st positive results in Illinois in
2004 for the mosquito-borne disease, Dr Eric E Whitaker, state public
health director, announced on Thu 13 May. Dr Whitaker said the Illinois
Department of Public Health was notified by DuPage County of the findings
as part of the county's routine surveillance for West Nile virus. The dead
crow was found Mon [10 May] in Downers Grove, and the mosquito pools were
collected on 6 May in Wayne, and, on Mon 10 May, in Darien. "Illinois has
seen West Nile virus activity during the past 3 years, and it is not a
surprise to see a positive test result reported in the spring," Dr.
Whitaker said. "These reports simply underscore the fact that the state and
local health departments have in place a very aggressive surveillance
effort for West Nile and other mosquitoborne diseases."

In 2003, the 1st positive bird for West Nile virus was reported on 21 May
in Henderson County. In all, in 2003, 75 of the state's 102 counties were
found to have a West Nile virus positive bird, mosquito, horse, or human
case. A total of 54 human cases of West Nile disease, including one
fatality, was reported in 2003 in Illinois. In 2002, the state led the
nation with 884 human cases (including 66 deaths), and West Nile activity
was reported in 100 of 102 counties.

Surveillance for West Nile virus began on 1 May 2004 and includes
collecting dead crows and blue jays. Citizens who observe a sick or dying
crow, or blue jay, should contact their local health department, which will
determine if the bird is to be picked up for testing. Additional
information about West Nile virus can be found on the Department's website:
.

